Can the euro be fixed?
Paris—Recently, German Finance Minister Wolfgang Schäuble has brought up the option of Greece leaving the euro, hoping to send a signal that no member state can be exempt from the strict discipline of the monetary union.
In fact, his proposal has sparked a big discussion about the principles that form the basis of the euro, the euro governance model, and the rationale for the existence of the euro.
Two weeks before Schäuble's proposal, European leaders had already noticed a report on the future of the euro written by European Commission President Jean-Claude Juncker and his colleagues from other EU institutions. However, the new debate over Greece has led many policymakers to believe it is necessary to return to the original starting point.
Meanwhile, citizens are questioning why they should share a common currency?
Does this make sense? Can we reach a consensus on the future of Greece?
Currency is like a nation; it requires a myth to establish it.
Traditional wisdom holds that the euro was the political price Germany paid to France in order to reunify.
In fact, German reunification was just the final step of an engineering project that had already taken shape in the 1980s to resolve a long-standing problem.
European governments strongly oppose floating exchange rates, considering them incompatible with a single market; at the same time, they are unwilling to maintain a monetary system dominated by the German central bank in the long term.
A truly European currency based on German principles seems to be the best solution.
In hindsight, German reunification was more of a curse than a blessing.
When exchange rates were locked in 1999, Germany was overvalued and its economy was in great difficulty; France was undervalued and its economy was thriving.
In the following decade, imbalances gradually re-emerged between the resurgent Germany and countries experiencing credit booms due to low interest rates.
And with the outbreak of the global financial crisis in 2008, these conditions became a breeding ground for a perfect storm.
No one knows what Europe would be like without the euro.
Would the fixed exchange rate system continue or collapse?
Would the German mark still be overvalued?
Would countries reintroduce trade barriers and end the single market?
Would a real estate bubble emerge in Spain?
Will government reform be more or less?
It is impossible to establish a baseline assessment of the impact of the euro through reverse analysis.
But this is certainly not a reason for complacency.
In the past 15 years, the economic performance of the eurozone has been disappointing, and its political institutions must be held responsible.
What is really important is whether a common European currency will still be important in the future.
This issue is often avoided because the cost of leaving the euro is unimaginably high (and if the disintegration of the eurozone occurs during a crisis and exacerbates mutual strife among member states, the costs would be even higher).
Furthermore, abolishing the euro could unleash the dark forces of nationalism and protectionism.
However, Kevin O’Rourke from the University of Oxford recently pointed out that this view is not sufficient.
Logically, this is equivalent to advising a couple to stay married simply because the cost of divorce is too high.
So, does the euro still make sense?
Originally, people expected the euro to bring three major economic benefits.
It was assumed that the currency union would promote economic integration and consolidate long-term growth in Europe.
On the contrary, trade and investment growth within the euro area have been mediocre, and the growth potential has actually weakened.
This is partly because national governments have not gone further on the basis of monetary unification to build the euro area into an economic superpower, but have tried to retain the remaining powers.
This may be politically logical, but it is economically worthless: Europe's huge internal market is one of its main assets, so it is absolutely necessary to seize the opportunity to strengthen the internal market.
Secondly, people hope that the euro will become one of the major international currencies (especially considering that few countries can meet the necessary legal, market, and policy institutions).
According to the latest data from the European Central Bank, this hope has basically been realized.
The international use of the euro ranks second to the US dollar, an achievement that helps Europe continue to influence the global economic order rather than becoming an irrelevant entity.
Thirdly, people (not without a touch of naivety) believe that the institutions underlying the euro can improve the overall quality of economic policy, as if the overall policy level of Europe were naturally higher than that of national policies.
After the 2008 global financial crisis, a severe test came: the eurozone overestimated the fiscal dimension of the crisis and underestimated its financial dimension, thus performing worse than the United States and the United Kingdom.
If the euro is to bring prosperity, further reforms of policy institutions are essential.
But setting and implementing an agenda requires a broad consensus on the nature of the problem.
The ongoing debates over Greece show that Europe is far from reaching a consensus: member states have conflicting analyses of the root causes of the debt crisis, and thus their prescriptions are also conflicting.
Richard Cooper from Harvard University once observed that in the early stages of international public health cooperation, global disease governance was greatly hindered by different transmission patterns in various countries.
Countries all favor joint action, but cannot form a unified plan because they have differing opinions on how infectious diseases spread from one country to another.
This is the problem the eurozone is facing today.
Fortunately, this problem is not unsolvable, and major reforms such as establishing the European Stability Mechanism (European Stability Mechanism) and launching the banking union have proven this point.
Inconsistencies have not prevented the European Central Bank from taking decisive action, which shows that institutional governance does indeed matter.
However, the fact that reforms and actions have only recently begun and were implemented under the pressure of a serious crisis makes us clearly aware of the difficulty of reaching consensus.
Europe can no longer procrastinate and pretend any longer.
The member states of the Eurozone must establish a unified agenda regarding governance and political reform to turn the currency union into an engine of prosperity; otherwise, they will only sink into repeated disputes and crises until citizens lose patience or markets lose confidence.
Clarity is a prerequisite for serious discussion and major reform.
Today, all major parties have the obligation to clearly define what they consider indispensable, what they find unacceptable, and what they are willing to offer in exchange for what they desire.
